    <item>
      <title>Re: VP - Good example of disconnect between players &amp; designers</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Veterans&amp;message.id=236227#M236227</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;BR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
Redi_Wolf wrote:&lt;BR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;One question regarding encounter design: do you tend to design a mob's abilities (and the other challenges of the event) with a particular solution in mind, or do you say "Let's give this mob a 3k dd, hatelist-based shadowstep, and adds that proc an aggro reducer, and see what the players figure out?"&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;BR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Depends on the encounter. Some of the encounters&amp;nbsp;I start with an outline of what we want it to do (how difficult it would be, how much HP/AC it has) and then I try and figure out how to make the encounter interesting. Sometimes though, the idea of what the encounter is about comes first, and then I fill in the blanks on how much HP/AC it has, what spells, etc. A good example of this is when I wrote up the Suchun raid. The main idea in my head was to make the encounter based on keeping your mana/endurance above a certain point, and if you didn't, you die. I then worked around that idea and made it into a 3 wave event, with portals/adds, mini-bosses, and a final boss at the end. I then expanded upon that event during testing, when players said "hey, it would be cool to add this" and in some situations I added it.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Feedback during the beta process can be really cool if you get a good guild to test - a guild that wants to test and make sure everything is correct. I rely a lot on player ideas for a lot of varied things on events. Some of you guys that have tested with me on beta know - I'm pretty open about making an event more fun (as well as killing players in the process).&lt;BR&gt;&lt;/P&gt;</description>
